---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Mukherjee et al. (2026) — Blue-dominant Lyα emission and gas inflow";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">BLUEPRINT: Blue-dominant Lyman-alpha (Lyα) emission as evidence of gas inflow in ultra-low-mass galaxies at z = 3</h1>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">BLUEPRINT: Blue-dominant Lyα emission</h3>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Type:</th>
          <td>Paper</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>First described:</th>
          <td>2026 (Mukherjee et al.)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Key Papers:</th>
          <td>
            <WikiLink slug="papers/mukherjee-2026-blue-dominant-lyalpha" text="Mukherjee et al. (2026)" />
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Related:</th>
          <td>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/cosmic-web-gas-accretion" text="Cosmic-web gas accretion" /><br>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/ultra-low-mass-galaxies" text="Ultra-low-mass galaxies" />
          </td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>
      <strong>Abstract:</strong> We report the detection of a clumpy, blue-dominated Lyα emission at z = 3.066 embedded in a cosmic-web filament, spatially associated with a primary galaxy and two compact ultra-low-mass star-forming components. Radiative transfer modelling using a clumpy multiphase model suggests radial inflow of neutral clumps with v_cl ≈ 98 km s⁻¹.<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <h2 id="key-findings">Key findings</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Radiative-transfer modelling indicates clump radial inflow v_cl ≈ 98 km s⁻¹ (Mukherjee et al. 2026; Sect. 3.2; Table 1; Fig. 2).<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup></li>
      <li>Lyα emission is extended, clumpy and offset from the main continuum peak; the structure lies within a ~4 cMpc cosmic-web filament (Sect. 2.1; Fig. 1).<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup></li>
      <li>Two compact components have ultra-low masses (log(M*/M☉) ≈ 6.3–6.9), very young ages (&lt;~7 Myr) and high sSFRs, consistent with recent bursty star formation (Sect. 3.3; Table 2; Fig. 6).<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup></li>
      <li>NFW modelling places the companion well inside the primary halo’s virial region and as a coherent sub-halo (Sect. 4.3; Fig. 4).<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup></li>
    </ol>

    <h2 id="discussion">Discussion</h2>
    <p>
      The coincidence of blue-dominant Lyα inflow signatures with extremely young, low-mass star-forming clumps supports a scenario in which cold accretion (cosmic-web or recycled) fuels localized starbursts in ultra-low-mass systems.<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup>
    </p>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li id="ref1">Mukherjee, T., Li, Z., Zafar, T., et al. 2026, "BLUEPRINT: Blue-dominant Lyman-alpha (Lyα) emission as an evidence of gas inflow in ultra-low-mass galaxies at z = 3", <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.2603.11411">arXiv:2603.11411</a> (submitted to A&amp;A).</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="page-tags">
